I thought this was very good. To answer the vodka versus wine question....vodka in this type of pasta sauce is a classic combination. I read (and make) a lot of recipes and I've actually seen vodka used more often than wine. I have a favourite recipe from an old issue of Bon Appetit that calls for vodka and some whipping cream together with onions and tomatoes, but no bacon or pancetta, to make a very similar sauce for penne pasta. Totally delicious but not that healthy, so I rarely make it these days. I wouldn't describe vodka as having a 'medicinal' taste at all - you just don't notice the flavour of the alcohol in the finished dish.

Rating: 0
Re vodka instead of white wine: I think it would change the flavour considerably, but probably not for the better. Vodka has a strong, biting and almost medicinal flavour, that is why it pairs so well with both sweet and tangy fruit juices. However, white vermouth is an excellent stand-in for white wine and I always keep a bottle in the pantry just for cooking purposes. As I recall, Julia Child also subs vermouth for white wine.

